=====Usage notes=====
* When the subject of a verb in the indicative mood is ''thou'', the verb usually ends in {{m|en|-est}}, in both the present and simple past tenses, as in “Lovest '''thou''' me?” (from John 21:17 of the King James Bible). This is the case even for modal verbs, which do not specially conjugate for the third person singular. Irregular forms include: {{m|en|art}} (of {{m|en|be}}), {{m|en|hast}} (of {{m|en|have}}), {{m|en|shalt}} (of {{m|en|shall}}), {{m|en|wost}} (of {{m|en|wit}}), {{m|en|wilt}} (of {{m|en|will}}), and {{m|en|dost}} (of {{m|en|do}}). [[must|''Must'']] does not change. In the subjunctive, as is normal, the bare form is usually used. However, ''[[beest]]'' is sometimes used instead of ''be''.
* Traditionally, use of ''thou'' and ''ye'' followed the [[w:T–V distinction|T–V distinction]], ''thou'' being the informal pronoun. This is preserved in the dialects in which ''thou'' is still in everyday use, but in Standard English, due to the pronoun’s association with religious texts and poetry, some speakers find it more solemn or even formal.

